<section xml:id="section-assignment1">
  <title>Assignment 1</title>
  <p><ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        Test the following series for convergence. (24)
        <ol>
          <li><me>
            \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{n^2 + 1}{n^3 - 4}
          </me></li>
          <li><me>
            \sum_{n=0}^\infty \left( \sqrt{\frac{1}{2}} \right)^{2n} 
          </me></li>
          <li><me>
            \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{1}{\pi - 3}^n 
          </me></li>
          <li><me>
            \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{(n+1)! (2n)!}{(n!)^3}
          </me></li>
          <li><me>
            \sum_{n=2}^\infty \frac{\ln n}{n^2} 
          </me></li>
          <li><me>
            \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{n^2 + n^3(\sin (n \pi))}{n^4 + 4}
          </me></li>
          <li><me>
            \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{(\ln n)^2}{n^2 + 1}
          </me></li>
          <li><me>
            \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{(-1)^n n^2}{n^2 + 4}
          </me></li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Calculate the Taylor series for each function, if possible,
        around the given centre point <m>\alpha</m> and determine the 
        radius of convergence. You can use commonly known series and 
        adapt them, or calculate directly using derivatives to determine
        the series. (20)
        <ol>
          <li>
            <md>
              <mrow>
                \amp \sin (6x^2) \amp \amp \alpha = 0
              </mrow>
            </md>
          </li>
          <li>
            <md>
              <mrow>
                \amp \frac{1}{1 - x^4} \amp \amp \alpha = 1
              </mrow>
            </md>
          </li>
          <li>
            <md>
              <mrow>
                \amp \ln x \amp \amp \alpha = e
              </mrow>
            </md>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Use the Lagrange error bounds to solve the following problems.
        (12)
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Given <m>\sin x</m> as a Taylor series centered at
              <m>0</m>, what interval allows the seventh order
              approximation to have accuracy <m>\frac{1}{1000}</m>.
              (You may approximate the interval to the nearest
              hundredth.) 
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Given <m>\ln x</m> as a Taylor series centered at
              <m>0</m>, what accuracy is guaranteed by using a tenth
              order approximation? 
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Given <m>\frac{1}{1-x}</m> as a Taylor series centered at
        <m>0</m>, show that the Lagrange error calculation cannot
        determine the order of approximation required to ensure that
        the error is less than <m>\frac{1}{1000}</m> on the interval
        <m>\left( \frac{-1}{2}, \frac{1}{2} \right)</m>? 
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Let <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> be positive continuous functions
        which both grow to inifnnity as <m>x \rightarrow \infty</m>.
        Assume that the following series has a finite, non-zero radius
        of convergence <m>R</m>. (10) 
        <me>
          \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{f(n)}{g(n)} x^n 
        </me>
        What happens to <m>R</m>, if anything, under the following
        changes. Be as specific as you can and give reasons. 
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f</m> is replace by <m>2f</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>g</m> is replace by <m>\frac{g}{3}</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f</m> is replace by <m>f^2</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>g</m> is replace by <m>g^3</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>g</m> is replace by <m>g+1</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
  </ol></p>
